  "enhanced_information": "Subacute combined degeneration of the spinal cord (SACD) is primarily associated with Vitamin B12 deficiency. This deficiency leads to a disruption in myelin synthesis, which is crucial for nerve fiber protection and signal transmission. The resulting demyelination specifically affects the spinal cord, leading directly to SACD. The evidence path linking demyelination to neurological disorders like Guillain-Barre Syndrome, although correct, is not directly relevant to SACD but confirms the role of demyelination in severe neurological conditions. Other vitamins such as Vitamin B6, Vitamin A, and Vitamin B9, though they have roles in neurological health or anemia, do not directly cause SACD. Vitamin B6 deficiency does lead to neurological symptoms, but these do not typically manifest as SACD. Vitamin A affects vision and immune function but has no direct link to myelin synthesis or spinal cord health. Vitamin B9 deficiency can lead to anemia and might have neurological complications, but it is not a typical cause of SACD."
